<body>
    <div id="header"></div>
    <div id="navigation"></div>

    <main class="content">
        <div class="content-group">
            <h1>Compost Tumblers</h1>
            
            <section class="intro">
                <h2>How Compost Tumblers Work</h2>
                <p>Compost tumblers are rotating containers that make mixing compost materials effortless. By simply turning the drum, you aerate the compost, introducing essential <a href="principles-of-composting/#Oxygen">oxygen</a> that speeds up decomposition.</p>
                
                <div class="columns">
                    <div class="column">
                        <h3>Key Features</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Fully enclosed design</li>
                            <li>Rotating mechanism for easy mixing</li>
                            <li>Can achieve hot composting temperatures</li>
                            <li>Produces compost in weeks</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="column">
                        <h3>Best Uses</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>All food waste (including cooked)</li>
                            <li>Perennial weeds</li>
                            <li>Small garden waste</li>
                            <li>When rodent-proofing is essential</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <p class="note">For best results, let finished compost mature in a ground-based bin before use to allow soil organisms to complete the process.</p>
            </section>
            
            <section class="pros-cons">
                <div class="column">
                    <h2>Advantages</h2>
                    <ul class="benefits">
                        <li><strong>Pest-proof</strong> - Fully enclosed design deters rodents</li>
                        <li><strong>Efficient</strong> - Can produce compost in 4-6 weeks</li>
                        <li><strong>Easy turning</strong> - No heavy shoveling required</li>
                        <li><strong>Versatile</strong> - Suitable for hot composting</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="column">
                    <h2>Considerations</h2>
                    <ul class="drawbacks">
                        <li>Higher initial cost than open bins</li>
                        <li>Requires significant space</li>
                        <li>Can become heavy when full</li>
                        <li>Needs careful material balance</li>
                        <li>Prone to fruit flies if too moist</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section class="instructions">
                <h2>Step-by-Step Guide</h2>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Site Selection</h3>
                        <p>Choose a level, accessible location with about 30cm clearance from fences. Partial shade helps regulate temperature and moisture.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Material Preparation</h3>
                        <p>Chop ingredients to 5cm pieces for faster decomposition. Mix wet greens with dry browns (especially woodchip) to prevent clumping.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Loading the Tumbler</h3>
                        <p>Follow manufacturer's ratios for greens and browns. Never fill more than 3/4 full to allow proper mixing.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Turning Routine</h3>
                        <p>Rotate the tumbler 5-10 times every 1-2 days. More frequent turning speeds decomposition.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Moisture Management</h3>
                        <p>Maintain a damp sponge consistency. Add water if dry, or more browns if too wet.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Maintenance</h3>
                        <p>Continue adding balanced materials and turning regularly until full. Then let it "cook" while starting a second batch.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h3>Harvesting</h3>
                        <p>When material is dark and crumbly (typically 4-8 weeks), remove and let mature in a ground bin for 1-2 months before use.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                
                <div class="tip">
                    <h3>Pro Tip</h3>
                    <p>Keep a bucket of woodchips nearby to mix with food scraps as you add them to maintain proper texture and carbon balance.</p>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </main>

    <div id="footer"></div>

    <script>
        // Component loading
        ['header', 'navigation', 'footer'].forEach(component => {
            fetch(`${component}.html`)
